As a former M&A guy, I always look forward to the =E2=80=9CBackground of th=
e Transaction=E2=80=9D section of the proxy, which is usually filed when th=
ere is a material transaction involving a public company=E2=80=94a merger, =
a move to go private, or some other change of control. And so, I=E2=80=99ve=
 been salivating to dive into the proxy related to the David Ellison-RedBir=
d Capital takeover of Paramount Global.

I was not disappointed. The proxy is chock-full of jilted suitors and mangl=
ed, muddled offers from both likely and unlikely suspects. It lays bare all=
 the machinations that took place for the six months or so between the star=
t of the sale process and its conclusion.

As you will recall, the Ellisons and RedBird are essentially replacing the =
Redstone family as the controlling shareholders of Paramount Global, inject=
ing new capital into
the company to pay down debt, combining Ellison=E2=80=99s Skydance Media wi=
th Paramount Pictures, and installing a new management team led by Jeff She=
ll. Paramount Global will remain a publicly traded company, controlled by D=
avid and his father, Larry Ellison, and the good folks at RedBird Capital.

You will also recall that, except for the ongoing regulatory approvals, whi=
ch will delay the closing until well into 2025=E2=80=94a broadcast license =
at CBS is being conveyed to new owners, after all=E2=80=94no shareholder vo=
te is required. Indeed, as the proxy makes clear=E2=80=94on page 164 of the=
 nearly 600-page document=E2=80=94the deal has already been approved by the=
 only shareholder that matters: Shari Redstone. Interestingly, the document=
 also makes clear, in bold type, that a proxy was not necessary since there=
 was no shareholder vote related to the deal. (Usually, a proxy statement i=
s prepared and filed=E2=80=94and costs related to it
incurred=E2=80=94so that shareholders will have all the information they ne=
ed to make a decision on whether to vote for a proposed transaction. That=
=E2=80=99s not the case here, since the Redstones made their decision and v=
oted their shares by written consent.) But I=E2=80=99m told the proxy was n=
ecessary because new Paramount securities are going to be issued as part of=
 the deal to its new owners, known for now as New Pluto Global Inc. (A new =
name is forthcoming.)

But let=E2=80=99s be thankful that a proxy has been filed. As a result, we =
can learn a variety of new things about the deal, a number of them highly s=
urprising.

Centerview=E2=80=99s Payday & Comcast Curiosities

First, my hat goes off to the special committee of the Paramount board of d=
irectors and its advisors at Cravath and Centerview. The proxy makes clear =
that they worked their asses off around the clock for seven months or so, s=
pending nearly every day on this one matter. Of course, the proxy also make=
s clear how well paid they were for their work. Cravath=E2=80=99s fees were=
 not disclosed in the proxy, but at $2,000-plus an hour, given the multitud=
e of meetings, Zooms, correspondence, and deal documents=E2=80=A6 that has =
got to add up. The proxy does confirm my reporting that Centerview is makin=
g around $60 million for its work on the deal, including a $51 million succ=
ess fee, a $2 million signing fee, a $2.5 million fee for issuing a fairnes=
s opinion, and payments of $250,000 a month.

My friend Blair Effron and his Centerview team worked
hard here, especially after Shari appeared to blow up the deal in July. Aft=
er the deal with Ellison and RedBird was consummated, Centerview contacted =
58 parties amid the contractual =E2=80=9Cgo shop=E2=80=9D period, seven of =
which kicked the tires, including the pathetic effort by Edgar Bronfman Jr.=
, who inevitably bowed out and cleared the way for the deep-pocketed Elliso=
ns. Still, even with all that work, it=E2=80=99s a nice payday for Centervi=
ew. The proxy revealed that the members of the special committee were also =
getting paid extra for their work: $10,000 a month each, from January onwar=
d, plus $2,000 per meeting and $1,000 per hour spent on =E2=80=9Clitigation=
-related matters=E2=80=9D pertaining to the assignment.

There were, according to the proxy, several more active competitors than pr=
eviously known, or at least well known. Take, for instance, Comcast=E2=80=
=94referred to in the proxy as =E2=80=9CParty B.=E2=80=9D Its effort to for=
m a streaming joint venture between Peacock and
Paramount+ is especially interesting in light of Mike Cavanagh=E2=80=99s co=
mments last Thursday that Comcast is open to considering just such a partne=
rship for its money-losing service. According to the proxy, on January 11, =
former Paramount C.E.O. Bob Bakish also spoke with Comcast C.E.O. Brian Rob=
erts about a full-scale acquisition=E2=80=94an idea that seems far-fetched =
given Comcast=E2=80=99s ownership of NBC and Paramount=E2=80=99s ownership =
of CBS, but whatevs.

In a January 26 meeting between Paramount management and Comcast management=
, Roberts explained that Comcast was no longer interested in a streaming jo=
int venture or buying Paramount. Instead, Brian said he wanted a licensing =
deal to get Paramount+ content on Peacock. But at a subsequent meeting, on =
February 20, Brian said he was interested in the streaming joint venture, s=
o long as Comcast had majority control. The special committee authorized th=
e streaming joint venture
discussions with Comcast, and those talks continued until April, including =
the sharing of confidential information covered by N.D.A.s. Two months! Who=
 knew?

In mid-March, Bakish actually recommended to the special committee that the=
 streaming pact with Comcast could be part of a =E2=80=9Cmulti-step plan,=
=E2=80=9D along with the sale of Paramount=E2=80=99s movie studio, to maxim=
ize value for shareholders and solve some of the company=E2=80=99s operatio=
nal problems. Bakish also told the committee that the streaming venture wit=
h Comcast would require =E2=80=9Ca substantial cash contribution=E2=80=9D o=
n Paramount=E2=80=99s part. The special committee then decided they had bet=
ter gauge Shari=E2=80=99s support for a sale of key Paramount assets before=
 deciding whether to move forward with Comcast. On March 30, Shari told the=
 special committee that she preferred that they enter into exclusive discus=
sions with Ellison/RedBird, even if it meant ending the dialogue with Comca=
st. And that was that.

Enter Zaslav

There were also the discussions with David Zaslav, at Warner Bros. Discover=
y, referred to as =E2=80=9CParty A=E2=80=9D in the proxy. As my partner Mat=
t Belloni explored ( https://puck.news/paramounts-deal-dance-costners-hubri=
s-clints-revenge/?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F6%2F24%29=
&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ) on Monday night, the conversations between WBD =
and Paramount were more extensive than previously known. On December 19, as=
 was reported at the time by Axios, Bakish and Zaz met to discuss a =E2=80=
=9Cbusiness combination=E2=80=9D between Paramount and WBD. On January 11, =
the special committee authorized Bakish to =E2=80=9Cengage directly=E2=80=
=9D with Zaz to talk about a deal. Bakish and Zaz spoke that day and
discussed convening a meeting among the broader management teams of the two=
 companies. The special committee then authorized the conversations with WB=
D to continue.

But on January 16, NAI=E2=80=99s advisors, BDT & MSD Partners, splashed som=
e cold water on further discussions with WBD. Byron Trott=E2=80=99s firm, w=
hich had made a $175 million preferred stock investment in NAI, noted that =
such a combination would =E2=80=9Cpose heightened regulatory risk,=E2=80=9D=
 causing long delays and potentially the further deterioration of Paramount=
=E2=80=99s business.

Still, despite BDT & MSD=E2=80=99s concerns, the special committee authoriz=
ed Cravath to negotiate an N.D.A. with WBD. For the next couple months, thr=
ough March 2024, WBD and Paramount conducted mutual due diligence. But at a=
 meeting on January 23, Bakish and Zaz decided that while a deal =E2=80=9Ch=
ad significant synergy potential,=E2=80=9D there were big problems, too, be=
cause =E2=80=9Cboth Paramount and [WBD] were highly levered and exposed to
challenging industry trends,=E2=80=9D according to the proxy. =E2=80=9CThe =
participants also discussed next steps with respect to exploring a potentia=
l business combination with [WBD], including the regulatory environment tha=
t such a transaction would likely encounter.=E2=80=9D

On February 21, after Paramount and WBD had shared lots of confidential inf=
ormation with each other, the special committee decided that nothing additi=
onal would be shared with WBD until an actual transaction proposal was subm=
itted. A week later, Zaz told Bakish on a call that he=E2=80=99d been in to=
uch with Shari at NAI, and realized that between her desire to receive cash=
 for her stake in Paramount, and her valuation expectations for that stake,=
 a deal between Paramount and WBD would be =E2=80=9Cchallenging.=E2=80=9D O=
n March 1, the special committee, apparently fed up with WBD and Zaz, =E2=
=80=9Cexpressed skepticism regarding [WBD=E2=80=99s] intentions.=E2=80=9D

That same day, WBD=E2=80=99s representatives told Centerview that, without
Shari=E2=80=99s support, it made little sense for WBD to pursue a deal for =
Paramount, which would be an all-stock transaction and therefore probably n=
ot in the cards. According to the proxy, WBD never actually submitted that =
transaction proposal. Still, on April 11, Zaz called Centerview and said WB=
D would still be interested=E2=80=A6 in an all-stock deal. He was hanging a=
round the hoop, but nothing came of it, and that was that.

The Apollo Moon Shot

There were other curious subplots to this saga. For instance, Apollo (=E2=
=80=9CParty C=E2=80=9D) was all over this thing pretty much from the outset=
, with a variety of creative and interesting ideas, none of which went very=
 far. On March 6, Apollo offered $11 billion for the Paramount studio and s=
ome of the company=E2=80=99s film and television studios. On March 22, the =
special committee decided to continue exploring =E2=80=9Cthe merits=E2=80=
=9D of Apollo=E2=80=99s proposal. Later that day, NAI informed the special =
committee that it would not support the sale to Apollo at anything like the=
 proposed $11 billion, or even for twice that amount.

The next day, Apollo sent a letter to the special committee adding that it =
would pay between $2.5 billion and $3 billion for all the voting shares of =
Paramount Global, including those owned by the Redstones=E2=80=94this
was new news=E2=80=94and might be willing to partner with third parties to =
buy all of Paramount. Then, on March 26, Apollo sent in a letter saying it =
wanted to buy all of Paramount, but without offering specifics.

On March 31, Apollo added the specifics=E2=80=94proposing to buy all of Par=
amount for between $26 billion and $27 billion, including the assumption of=
 Paramount=E2=80=99s debt. But NAI still viewed the Apollo proposal as =E2=
=80=9Cnot an actionable offer=E2=80=9D and not worth risking the Ellison/Re=
dBird deal. (Why Shari felt that way is not clear=E2=80=94$27 billion seems=
 like a generous price for Paramount.) On April 2, Apollo sent another lett=
er: Its offer would be all-cash, and it had plenty of money to support the =
purchase price of the equity. On April 3, though, the special committee opt=
ed to give exclusivity to Ellison/RedBird anyway.

The next anyone heard from Apollo was on May 1, when the firm sent a letter=
 to the special committee outlining a $26 billion all-cash
offer=E2=80=94noting they were now teamed up with Sony Pictures=E2=80=94to =
buy all of Paramount Global at $28 a share for the voting stock and $17 a s=
hare for the nonvoting stock, premiums of 35 percent and 49 percent, respec=
tively, from where those shares were trading. They also offered to acquire =
the Redstones=E2=80=99 stock in Paramount for $1.8 billion. On May 16, the =
two sides executed an N.D.A.

But the special committee and its advisors eventually complained about the =
=E2=80=9Cslow pace=E2=80=9D of the discussions with Apollo and Sony=E2=80=
=94likely because of the increasing regulatory concerns about a combination=
 between Sony and Paramount. On May 27, the pace of the discussions with Ap=
ollo and Sony was so slow that the advisors to the special committee determ=
ined that Ellison/RedBird was the best option, and maybe the only one. Fina=
lly, when a potential deal with Sony appeared to come a cropper, on July 3,=
 Apollo sent a new letter, offering to make a $4 billion preferred equity
investment in Paramount that the company could use to deleverage its capita=
l structure and buy back stock. But that proposal went nowhere, too. Apollo=
=E2=80=940 for 4. The Ellison/RedBird deal was announced on July 7.

=E2=80=9CParty F=E2=80=9D

There remain a number of mystery bidders, referred to only by capital lette=
rs in the proxy. The one that intrigues me most is =E2=80=9CParty F,=E2=80=
=9D a private-equity firm focused on middle-market companies. On February 2=
9, Party F sent a letter to Bakish and Shari offering to contribute an =E2=
=80=9Centertainment studio=E2=80=9D it owned to Paramount in exchange for a=
 19.9 percent stake in Paramount Global. Party F also wanted Paramount to e=
nd its dual-class stock structure and offered to pay a to-be-determined amo=
unt to the voting shareholders in exchange for their rights, in effect maki=
ng Party F the new controlling shareholder simply by contributing its =E2=
=80=9Centertainment studio=E2=80=9D and offering some cash. Nice work if yo=
u can get it.

No surprise, the proposal was of little interest. On April 17, Party F cont=
acted Shari again about its proposal. But she did
not respond. Centerview spoke with Party F on May 26, but there was no indi=
cation that it was willing to sweeten its offer. On June 6, Party F again t=
ried with NAI, but that effort also went nowhere. Who the heck is Party F? =
I=E2=80=99d like to know. (Please send me your best guesses and I=E2=80=99l=
l share them in a future edition of Dry Powder.)

Anyway, it=E2=80=99s fair to say the special committee and its advisors did=
 their job, and were well compensated for their efforts. You may not like t=
he Ellison/RedBird deal for Paramount, and the stock may never achieve the =
$30 to $40 a share that the new owners are hoping for, but you can=E2=80=99=
t say that any stone was left unturned in pursuit of the ultimate buyer for=
 the company.

