 I=E2=80=99m <b>Bill Cohan</b>.<br/><br/>While we all attempt to make sense=
 of whatever the hell just happened=E2=80=94I=E2=80=99ve got some thoughts =
on today=E2=80=99s stock market explosion below=E2=80=94tonight, I=E2=80=99=
m digging into the revelatory, 600-page proxy statement chronicling <b>Davi=
d Ellison</b> and RedBird Capital=E2=80=99s takeover of Paramount Global. I=
t=E2=80=99s a surreal corporate saga, chock-full of jilted suitors and mang=
led offers, that may provide a bit of levity amid the all-consuming news ou=
t of Washington. <br/><br/><i>But first=E2=80=A6</i><br/><br/></p><ul style=
=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>Measu=
ring the Trump bump on Wall Street</i>: While the repercussions of <b>Trump=
</b>=E2=80=99s emphatic victory last night continue to reverberate througho=
ut the
country=E2=80=94I guess the election wasn=E2=80=99t rigged after all=E2=80=
=94it=E2=80=99s making quite a statement on Wall Street, too. For reasons t=
hat are a little hard to fathom given how much the stock markets have alrea=
dy advanced in 2024, they <i>exploded</i> on Wednesday in the wake of Trump=
=E2=80=99s return. Those of us old enough to remember Trump 1.0, eight year=
s ago, will recall that after he squeaked out his shocking victory over <b>=
Hillary Clinton</b>, the stock markets crashed 1,000 points overnight, on a=
 much smaller Dow Jones Industrial Average number. This time, the DJIA skyr=
ocketed, up some 1,500 points, or 3.6 percent, while the Nasdaq was up 544 =
points, or 3 percent. <br/><br/>Other indicators of market sentiment also r=
ose. Bitcoin traded up nearly 8 percent to a new high of around $75,000 per=
 coin. The dollar rose, too, against a basket of currencies. This has been =
dubbed generally =E2=80=9CThe Trump Trade,=E2=80=9D as investors reset thei=
r bets for whatever it is they believe Trump II will be
about. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a lot of emotion, there=E2=80=99s a lot of =
euphoria, based on perspective in markets today,=E2=80=9D <b>Marta</b> <b>N=
orton</b>, chief investment strategist at Empower Investments, told CNBC. =
=E2=80=9CThat doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily mean that=E2=80=99s the way marke=
ts are going to trade in perpetuity.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>On the other hand, =
the yield on the 10-year Treasury shot up, to 4.45 percent, from around 4.2=
5 percent the day before, with a corresponding drop in the price of the 10-=
year bond, probably out of concern for the changes coming in Trump=E2=80=99=
s fiscal policy and what his new chairman of the Federal Reserve will do to=
 monetary policy. (Bye bye, <b>Jay</b> <b>Powell</b>, you had a nice run.) =
Another new Trump bellwether, Tesla, was up 15 percent on the day. <b>Elon =
Musk</b> is now worth $264 billion. <br/><br/>Meanwhile, the roller coaster=
 that is DJT stock=E2=80=94Trump Media and Technology=E2=80=94which many pr=
ognosticators thought might hit $100 a share with a Trump victory, opened a=
t
around $45 a share, up 32 percent from yesterday=E2=80=99s close. But the s=
tock has since come back to Earth somewhat, up around 6 percent on the day,=
 to around $36 per share. The people who bought at $45 a share have my symp=
athy. Where any of this goes from here is anyone=E2=80=99s guess. </li></ul=
