         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s3">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">First, my hat goes =
off to the special committee of the Paramount board of directors and its ad=
visors at Cravath and Centerview. The proxy makes clear that they worked th=
eir asses off around the clock for seven months or so, spending nearly ever=
y day on this one matter. Of course, the proxy also makes clear how well pa=
id they were for their work. Cravath=E2=80=99s fees were not disclosed in t=
he proxy, but at $2,000-plus an hour, given the multitude of meetings, Zoom=
s, correspondence, and deal documents=E2=80=A6 that has got to add up. The =
proxy does confirm my reporting that Centerview is making around $60 millio=
n for its work on the deal, including a $51 million success fee, a $2 milli=
on signing fee, a $2.5 million fee for issuing a fairness opinion, and paym=
ents of $250,000 a month. <br/><br/>My friend <b>Blair</b> <b>Effron</b> an=
d his Centerview team worked
hard here, especially after Shari appeared to blow up the deal in July. Aft=
er the deal with Ellison and RedBird was consummated, Centerview contacted =
58 parties amid the contractual =E2=80=9Cgo shop=E2=80=9D period, seven of =
which kicked the tires, including the pathetic effort by <b>Edgar</b> <b>Br=
onfman</b> <b>Jr.</b>, who inevitably bowed out and cleared the way for the=
 deep-pocketed Ellisons. Still, even with all that work, it=E2=80=99s a nic=
e payday for Centerview. The proxy revealed that the members of the special=
 committee were also getting paid extra for their work: $10,000 a month eac=
h, from January onward, plus $2,000 per meeting and $1,000 per hour spent o=
n =E2=80=9Clitigation-related matters=E2=80=9D pertaining to the assignment=
=2E<br/><br/>There were, according to t=
he proxy, several more active competit=
ors than previously known, or at least well known. Take, for instance, Comc=
ast=E2=80=94referred to in the proxy as =E2=80=9CParty B.=E2=80=9D Its effo=
rt to form a streaming joint venture between Peacock and
Paramount+ is especially interesting in light of <b>Mike</b> <b>Cavanagh</b=
>=E2=80=99s comments last Thursday that Comcast is open to considering just=
 such a partnership for its money-losing service. According to the proxy, o=
n January 11, former Paramount C.E.O. <b>Bob</b> <b>Bakish</b> also spoke w=
ith Comcast C.E.O. <b>Brian</b> <b>Roberts</b> about a full-scale acquisiti=
on=E2=80=94an idea that seems far-fetched given Comcast=E2=80=99s ownership=
 of NBC and Paramount=E2=80=99s ownership of CBS, but whatevs. <br/><br/>In=
 a January 26 meeting between Paramount management and Comcast management, =
Roberts explained that Comcast was no longer interested in a streaming join=
t venture <i>or</i> buying Paramount. Instead, Brian said he wanted a licen=
sing deal to get Paramount+ content on Peacock. But at a subsequent meeting=
, on February 20, Brian said he <i>was</i> interested in the streaming join=
t venture, so long as Comcast had majority control. The special committee a=
uthorized the streaming joint venture
discussions with Comcast, and those talks continued until April, including =
the sharing of confidential information covered by N.D.A.s. Two months! Who=
 knew?<br/><br/>In mid-March, Bakish actually recommended to the special co=
mmittee that the streaming pact with Comcast could be part of a =E2=80=9Cmu=
lti-step plan,=E2=80=9D along with the sale of Paramount=E2=80=99s movie st=
udio, to maximize value for shareholders and solve some of the company=E2=
=80=99s operational problems. Bakish also told the committee that the strea=
ming venture with Comcast would require =E2=80=9Ca substantial cash contrib=
ution=E2=80=9D on Paramount=E2=80=99s part. The special committee then deci=
ded they had better gauge Shari=E2=80=99s support for a sale of key Paramou=
nt assets before deciding whether to move forward with Comcast. On March 30=
, Shari told the special committee that she preferred that they enter into =
exclusive discussions with Ellison/RedBird, even if it meant ending the dia=
logue with Comcast. And that was that.<br/></td>
         </tr>
