x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">There were also the=
 discussions with <b>David</b> <b>Zaslav</b>, at Warner Bros. Discovery, re=
ferred to as =E2=80=9CParty A=E2=80=9D in the proxy. As my partner <b>Matt<=
/b> <b>Belloni</b> <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZC=
I6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUQTdUakdQUC0wNkRURXJrZzFEWT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0c=
HM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvcGFyYW1vdW50cy1kZWFsLWRhbmNlLWNvc3RuZXJzLWh1YnJpcy1jbGlu=
dHMtcmV2ZW5nZS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPURyeStQb3dkZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMSU=
yRjYlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW8iLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2Yz=
YwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjE5NjY1NTR9/ef1cc8b3827ebac0016ac4873bd5=
54e1cbda8362a085375b2fff86296a79f236" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoratio=
n:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">explored</a></u> on Monday night, th=
e conversations between WBD and Paramount were more extensive than previous=
ly known. On December 19, as was reported at the time by Axios, Bakish and =
Zaz met to discuss a =E2=80=9Cbusiness combination=E2=80=9D between Paramou=
nt and WBD. On January 11, the special committee authorized Bakish to =E2=
=80=9Cengage directly=E2=80=9D with Zaz to talk about a deal. Bakish and Za=
z spoke that day and
discussed convening a meeting among the broader management teams of the two=
 companies. The special committee then authorized the conversations with WB=
D to continue.<br/><br/>But on January 16, NAI=E2=80=99s advisors, BDT &amp=
; MSD Partners, splashed some cold water on further discussions with WBD. <=
b>Byron Trott</b>=E2=80=99s firm, which had made a $175 million preferred s=
tock investment in NAI, noted that such a combination would =E2=80=9Cpose h=
eightened regulatory risk,=E2=80=9D causing long delays and potentially the=
 further deterioration of Paramount=E2=80=99s business. <br/><br/>Still, de=
spite BDT &amp; MSD=E2=80=99s concerns, the special committee authorized Cr=
avath to negotiate an N.D.A. with WBD. For the next couple months, through =
March 2024, WBD and Paramount conducted mutual due diligence. But at a meet=
ing on January 23, Bakish and Zaz decided that while a deal =E2=80=9Chad si=
gnificant synergy potential,=E2=80=9D there were big problems, too, because=
 =E2=80=9Cboth Paramount and [WBD] were highly levered and exposed to
challenging industry trends,=E2=80=9D according to the proxy. =E2=80=9CThe =
participants also discussed next steps with respect to exploring a potentia=
l business combination with [WBD], including the regulatory environment tha=
t such a transaction would likely encounter.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>On February=
 21, after Paramount and WBD had shared lots of confidential information wi=
th each other, the special committee decided that nothing additional would =
be shared with WBD until an actual transaction proposal was submitted. A we=
ek later, Zaz told Bakish on a call that he=E2=80=99d been in touch with Sh=
ari at NAI, and realized that between her desire to receive cash for her st=
ake in Paramount, and her valuation expectations for that stake, a deal bet=
ween Paramount and WBD would be =E2=80=9Cchallenging.=E2=80=9D On March 1, =
the special committee, apparently fed up with WBD and Zaz, =E2=80=9Cexpress=
ed skepticism regarding [WBD=E2=80=99s] intentions.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>That=
 same day, WBD=E2=80=99s representatives told Centerview that, without
Shari=E2=80=99s support, it made little sense for WBD to pursue a deal for =
Paramount, which would be an all-stock transaction and therefore probably n=
ot in the cards. According to the proxy, WBD never actually submitted that =
transaction proposal. Still, on April 11, Zaz called Centerview and said WB=
D would <i>still</i> be interested=E2=80=A6 in an all-stock deal. He was ha=
nging around the hoop, but nothing came of it, and that was that.<br/></td>
         </tr>
