          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">There were other cu=
rious subplots to this saga. For instance, Apollo (=E2=80=9CParty C=E2=80=
=9D) was all over this thing pretty much from the outset, with a variety of=
 creative and interesting ideas, none of which went very far. On March 6, A=
pollo offered $11 billion for the Paramount studio and some of the company=
=E2=80=99s film and television studios. On March 22, the special committee =
decided to continue exploring =E2=80=9Cthe merits=E2=80=9D of Apollo=E2=80=
=99s proposal. Later that day, NAI informed the special committee that it w=
ould <i>not </i>support the sale to Apollo at anything like the proposed $1=
1 billion, or even for <i>twice</i> that amount. <br/><br/>The next day, Ap=
ollo sent a letter to the special committee adding that it would pay betwee=
n $2.5 billion and $3 billion for <i>all</i> the voting shares of Paramount=
 Global, including those owned by the Redstones=E2=80=94this
was new news=E2=80=94and might be willing to partner with third parties to =
buy all of Paramount. Then, on March 26, Apollo sent in a letter saying it =
wanted to buy all of Paramount, but without offering specifics. <br/><br/>O=
n March 31, Apollo added the specifics=E2=80=94proposing to buy all of Para=
mount for between $26 billion and $27 billion, including the assumption of =
Paramount=E2=80=99s debt. But NAI still viewed the Apollo proposal as =E2=
=80=9Cnot an actionable offer=E2=80=9D and not worth risking the Ellison/Re=
dBird deal. (Why Shari felt that way is not clear=E2=80=94$27 billion seems=
 like a generous price for Paramount.) On April 2, Apollo sent another lett=
er: Its offer would be all-cash, and it had plenty of money to support the =
purchase price of the equity. On April 3, though, the special committee opt=
ed to give exclusivity to Ellison/RedBird anyway. <br/><br/>The next anyone=
 heard from Apollo was on May 1, when the firm sent a letter to the special=
 committee outlining a $26 billion all-cash
offer=E2=80=94noting they were now teamed up with Sony Pictures=E2=80=94to =
buy all of Paramount Global at $28 a share for the voting stock and $17 a s=
hare for the nonvoting stock, premiums of 35 percent and 49 percent, respec=
tively, from where those shares were trading. They also offered to acquire =
the Redstones=E2=80=99 stock in Paramount for $1.8 billion. On May 16, the =
two sides executed an N.D.A. <br/><br/>But the special committee and its ad=
visors eventually complained about the =E2=80=9Cslow pace=E2=80=9D of the d=
iscussions with Apollo and Sony=E2=80=94likely because of the increasing re=
gulatory concerns about a combination between Sony and Paramount. On May 27=
, the pace of the discussions with Apollo and Sony was so slow that the adv=
isors to the special committee determined that Ellison/RedBird was the best=
 option, and maybe the <i>only </i>one. Finally, when a potential deal with=
 Sony appeared to come a cropper, on July 3, Apollo sent a new letter, offe=
ring to make a $4 billion preferred equity
investment in Paramount that the company could use to deleverage its capita=
l structure and buy back stock. But that proposal went nowhere, too. Apollo=
=E2=80=940 for 4. The Ellison/RedBird deal was announced on July 7.<br/></t=
d>
