          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">There remain a numb=
er of mystery bidders, referred to only by capital letters in the proxy. Th=
e one that intrigues me most is =E2=80=9CParty F,=E2=80=9D a private-equity=
 firm focused on middle-market companies. On February 29, Party F sent a le=
tter to Bakish and Shari offering to contribute an =E2=80=9Centertainment s=
tudio=E2=80=9D it owned to Paramount in exchange for a 19.9 percent stake i=
n Paramount Global. Party F also wanted Paramount to end its dual-class sto=
ck structure and offered to pay a to-be-determined amount to the voting sha=
reholders in exchange for their rights, in effect making Party F the new co=
ntrolling shareholder simply by contributing its =E2=80=9Centertainment stu=
dio=E2=80=9D and offering some cash. Nice work if you can get it. <br/><br/=
>No surprise, the proposal was of little interest. On April 17, Party F con=
